Retrieving Data

In this example, we use a data set from the tsibbledata package, nyc_bikes (https://github.com/tidyverts/tsibbledata). nyc_bikes contains information on trips taken in 2018 using NYC rental bikes. The bike_id helps to uniquely identify each observation, and the start_time serves as the index. It is an irregular tsibble, because bike rentals occur at different time intervals.

As a first step, please assign the data frame to an object and check its format.

example <- nyc_bikes

Working with our Tsibble

#Exercise 1 At the end of this exercise, we want to illustrate for how long different customers have used the bikes. We want to differentiate customers by birth year and gender.

#clean up the gender column
example %>% count(gender == "Unknown")
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   `gender == "Unknown"`     n
##   <lgl>                 <int>
## 1 FALSE                  3999
## 2 TRUE                    269
bikes_nyc <- filter(example, gender != "Unknown")

bikes_nyc %>% count(gender)
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   gender     n
##   <fct>  <int>
## 1 Male    3069
## 2 Female   930
#calculate the renting duration and update the tsibble
class(example$start_time)
## [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt"
class(example$stop_time)
## [1] "POSIXct" "POSIXt"
bikes <- bikes_nyc %>%
  group_by_key(c(gender, type)) %>%
  mutate(duration = difftime(stop_time, start_time,
                             units = "mins")) %>%
  update_tsibble(index = duration, 
                 validate = FALSE)

Plot the results for a visual overview of the data

class(bikes$duration)
## [1] "difftime"
bikes$duration <- as.numeric(bikes$duration)

ggplot(bikes, aes(x = duration)) + geom_histogram() + xlim(0, 150)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

ggplot(bikes_nyc, aes(x = birth_year, y = bikes$duration, color = gender)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2) + scale_x_continuous() + scale_y_time() + 
  ylim(0, 60) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + 
  facet_wrap(~month(bikes_nyc$start_time)) + 
  labs(x = "Year of Birth", y = "Duration of Trip in Minutes", color = 
         "Gender")
## Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
## replace the existing scale.

#Exercise 2 The goal of this exercise is again a visualisation of certain information we can obtain through the nyc_bikes data set.

Here, you can practice how to set up a tsibble. Because we use the same data set as before, you do not need to check and tidy the data again.

nycbikes_ts <- nyc_bikes %>% 
   as_tsibble(key = bike_id, index = start_time, regular = FALSE)

But we want to transform the temporal data a bit differently this time around - measuring the duration of trips in minutes without decimals and compute a variable that contains the start hour for each rented bike.

nyc2 <- nycbikes_ts %>% mutate(duration_mins = as.numeric(
   round(difftime(stop_time, start_time, units = "mins"),0)))

#index by start_hour
nyc2 %>% 
   index_by(start_hour = floor_date(start_time, unit = "1 hour"))
## # A tsibble: 4,268 x 14 [!] <America/New_York>
## # Key:       bike_id [10]
## # Groups:    @ start_hour [2,605]
##    bike_id start_time          stop_time           start_station start_lat
##    <fct>   <dttm>              <dttm>              <fct>             <dbl>
##  1 26301   2018-02-26 19:11:03 2018-02-26 19:15:40 3186               40.7
##  2 26301   2018-02-27 07:52:49 2018-02-27 07:58:13 3203               40.7
##  3 26301   2018-02-27 12:03:27 2018-02-27 12:04:54 3202               40.7

## 10 26301   2018-02-27 22:08:55 2018-02-27 22:28:42 3638               40.7
## #  with 4,258 more rows, and 9 more variables: start_long <dbl>,
## #   end_station <fct>, end_lat <dbl>, end_long <dbl>, type <fct>,
## #   birth_year <dbl>, gender <fct>, duration_mins <dbl>, start_hour <dttm>
#extract general start hour and date from more specific timestamp data
nyc3 <- nyc2 %>% 
   mutate(start_hour = floor_date(start_time, unit = "1 hour")) %>% 
   mutate(date = as_date(start_hour), time = hour(start_hour)) %>% 
   filter(gender != "Unknown")

#differentiate again by gender
nyc3 %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = duration_mins, colour = gender)) + 
   geom_point(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) + ylim(0, 120) + labs(x = "Date", 
              y = "Duration in Minutes", color = "Gender", title = 
                "Length of trips over the year by gender")
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Now we plot again. This time, please visualise the duration of rentals noting the different kind of users, customers who have a subscription and one-time users.

nyc3 %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = duration_mins, colour = type)) + 
   geom_point(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) + ylim(0, 120) + labs(x = "Date", 
              y = "Duration in Minutes", color = "Type", title = 
                "Length of trips over the year by subscription type")
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Also very interesting (and great to do with tsibble :-)) is to look at the rate of people renting bikes over the year.

#summarize total number of trips by hour, using the start hour as index
hourly_trips <- nyc2 %>% 
   index_by(start_hour = floor_date(start_time, unit = "1 hour")) %>% 
   summarise(ntrips = n())

#fill any gaps, and add column for date
full_trips <- hourly_trips %>% 
   fill_gaps(ntrips = 0L) %>%
   mutate(date = as_date(start_hour), time = hour(start_hour), 
          month = month(date))

#visualise trips per hour by date over the course of the year
full_trips %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = ntrips)) + geom_line() + 
  labs(x = "Date", y = "Trips per hour and bike")

#plotting a smoothing line, we find that the number of trips are highly 
#correlated with the seasons, declining as the weather gets colder.
full_trips %>% ggplot(aes(x = month, y = ntrips)) + geom_smooth() + 
   scale_x_discrete(limits = month.abb) + labs(x = "Month")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
